> Login should work with valid credentials

Then write code.

---

 ğŸŸ¦ 3. Continuous Integration

 Technical

Developers push code daily.
Automated testing runs.

Bugs detected early.

---

 ğŸ‘©â€â¤ï¸â€ğŸ‘¨ Example

Taste food while cooking.
Not after burning.

---

 ğŸ¢ IT example

Developer pushes code â†’ Jenkins runs tests â†’ errors found immediately.

---

 ğŸŸ¦ 4. Small releases

 Technical

Release small features frequently.

Instead of 6-month big release.

---

 ğŸ‘©â€â¤ï¸â€ğŸ‘¨ Example

Instead of cooking 10 dishes at once,
serve hot chapati one by one.

Better quality.

---

 ğŸŸª FINAL TECHNICAL DIFFERENCE

| Method | Best for            | Why               |
| ------ | ------------------- | ----------------- |
| Scrum  | Feature development | Planned work      |
| Kanban | Support/maintenance | Continuous work   |
| XP     | Critical systems    | High quality code |

---

 ğŸ¯ Interview Question (must know)

 Q: Why Kanban when Scrum exists?

Technical Answer:
Scrum is suitable for planned sprint-based development.
However, it is not flexible for continuous and urgent work like production support.
Kanban provides continuous workflow, flexible priorities, and no sprint restriction, making it suitable for support and DevOps teams.

